# Human-Sounding Copy

Applies to UI strings, i18n values, landing/marketing text, docs, commit messages, PR bodies, and replies to the user.

## Do not sound like a model

- Write like a clear teammate. Short sentences. Concrete words.
- Prefer plain phrasing over polished brochure tone.
- Do not stack synonyms, throat-clearing, or filler openers ("In today's world", "It's important to note", "Let's dive in").
- Avoid hype adjectives and empty intensifiers ("seamless", "robust", "cutting-edge", "powerful", "unlock", "elevate", "leverage").
- Avoid parallel marketing cadence ("Play local. Win real. Feel alive.") unless the existing brand voice already uses it.
- Do not over-explain. Say the useful thing once.

## Punctuation tells

- Never use em dashes (`—`) or en dashes (`–`) in user-facing or conversational text. Use a comma, period, colon, parentheses, or a separate sentence instead.
- Avoid emoji decoration in product copy unless the user or existing UI already uses it.
- Avoid neat three-item rhetorical lists when two points are enough.

## Examples

```text
Bad: Play smart — win real money with seamless MoMo payouts.
Good: Play smart. Win real money with MoMo payouts.

Bad: Unlock a powerful, seamless experience designed to elevate your game.
Good: Create or join a match in a few taps.

Bad: It's important to note that winners receive 75% of the pot.
Good: Winners get 75% of the pot.
```

## When editing existing copy

- Match the voice already in nearby strings for that locale.
- Do not "polish" copy into generic AI tone while translating or refactoring.
